# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: log4j-logging-java
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A **Java logging framework** is a computer data logging package for the Java platform.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This article covers general purpose logging frameworks.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging refers to the recording of activity by an application and is a common issue for development teams.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging frameworks ease and standardize the process of logging for the Java platform.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] In particular they provide flexibility by avoiding explicit output to the console (see Appender below).
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Where logs are written becomes independent of the code and can be customized at runtime.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Unfortunately the JDK did not include logging in its original release so by the time the Java Logging API was added several other logging frameworks had become widely used – in particular Apache Commons Logging (also known as Java Commons Logging or JCL) and Log4j.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This led to problems when integrating different third-party libraries (JARs) each using different logging frameworks.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Pluggable logging frameworks (wrappers) were developed to solve this problem.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging is typically broken into three major pieces: the Logger, the Formatter and the Appender (or Handler).
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Simpler logging frameworks, like |Java Logging Framework by the Object Guy, combine the logger and the appender.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This simplifies default operation, but it is less configurable, especially if the project is moved across environments.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A Logger is an object that allows the application to log without regard to where the output is sent/stored.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The application logs a message by passing an object or an object and an exception with an optional severity level to the logger object under a given name/identifier.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The name is usually structured hierarchically, with periods (.) separating the levels.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A common scheme is to use the name of the class or package that is doing the logging.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Both Log4j and the Java logging API support defining handlers higher up the hierarchy.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] For example, the logger might be named "`com.sun.some.UsefulClass`".
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] As long as there is a handler defined somewhere in this stack, logging may occur.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] For example a message logged to the `com.sun.some.UsefulClass` logger, may get written by the `com.sun` handler.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Typically there is a global handler that receives and processes messages generated by any logger.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The message is logged at a certain level.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The logging framework maintains the current logging level for each logger.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The logging level can be set more or less restrictive.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] For example, if the logging level is set to "WARNING", then all messages of that level or higher are logged: ERROR and FATAL.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Severity levels can be assigned to both loggers and appenders.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Both must be enabled for a given severity level for output to be generated.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] So a logger enabled for debug output will not generate output if the handler that gets the message is not also enabled for debug.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Filters cause a log event to be ignored or logged.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The most commonly used filter is the logging level documented in the previous section.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging frameworks such as Log4j 2 and SLF4J also provide Markers, which when attached to a log event can also be used for filtering.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Filters can also be used to accept or deny log events based on exceptions being thrown, data within the log message, data in a ThreadLocal that is exposed through the logging API, or a variety of other methods.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A Formatter is an object that formats a given object.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Mostly this consists of taking the binary object and converting it to a string representation.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Each framework defines a default output format that can be overridden if desired.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Appenders listen for messages at or above a specified minimum severity level.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The Appender takes the message it is passed and posts it appropriately.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] JCL and Log4j are very common simply because they have been around for so long and were the only choices for a long time.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The flexibility of slf4j (using Logback underneath) has made it a popular choice.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] SLF4J is a set of logging wrappers (or shims) that allow it to imitate any of the other frameworks.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Thus multiple third-party libraries can be incorporated into an application, regardless of the logging framework each has chosen to use.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] However all logging output is generated in a standard way, typically via Logback.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Log4j 2 provides both an API and an implementation.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The API can be routed to other logging implementations equivalent to how SLF4J works.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Unlike SLF4J, the Log4j 2 API logs Message objects instead of Strings for extra flexibility and also supports Java Lambda expressions.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] JCL isn't really a logging framework, but a wrapper for one.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] As such, it requires a logging framework underneath it, although it can default to using its own `SimpleLog` logger.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] JCL, SLF4J and the Log4j 2 API are useful when developing reusable libraries which need to write to whichever underlying logging system is being used by the application.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This also provides flexibility in heterogeneous environments where the logging framework is likely to change, although in most cases, once a logging framework has been chosen, there is little need to change it over the life of the project.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] SLF4J and Log4j 2 benefit from being newer and build on the lessons learned from older frameworks.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Moreover JCL has known problems with class-loaders when determining what logging library it should wrap which has now replaced JCL.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The Java Logging API is provided with Java.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Although the API is technically separate from the default implementation provided with Java, replacing it with an alternate implementation can be challenging so many developers confuse this implementation with the Java Logging API.
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Configuration is by external files only which is not easily changed on the fly (other frameworks support programmatic configuration).
[src:log4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The default implementation only provides a few Handlers and Formatters which means most users will have to write their own.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Apache **Log4j** is a Java-based logging utility originally written by Ceki Gülcü.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] It is part of the Apache Logging Services, a project of the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j is one of several Java logging frameworks.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Gülcü has since created SLF4J, Reload4j, and Logback which are alternatives to Log4j.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The Apache Log4j team developed Log4j 2 in response to the problems of Log4j 1.2, 1.3, `java.util.logging` and Logback, addressing issues which appeared in those frameworks.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] In addition, Log4j 2 offered a plugin architecture which makes it more extensible than its predecessor.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j 2 is not backwards compatible with 1.x versions, although an "adapter" is available.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] On August 5, 2015, the Apache Logging Services Project Management Committee announced that Log4j 1 had reached end of life and that users of Log4j 1 were advised to upgrade to Apache Log4j 2.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] On January 12, 2022, a forked and renamed log4j version 1.2 was released by Ceki Gülcü as Reload4j version 1.2.18.0 with the aim of fixing the most urgent issues in log4j 1.2.17 that had accumulated since its release in 2013.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] On December 9, 2021, a zero-day vulnerability involving arbitrary code execution in Log4j 2 was published by the Alibaba Cloud Security Team and given the descriptor "Log4Shell".
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] It has been characterized by Tenable as "the single biggest, most critical vulnerability of the last decade".
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Apache Log4j 2 is the successor of Log4j 1 which was released as GA version in July 2015.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The framework was rewritten from scratch and has been inspired by existing logging solutions, including Log4j 1 and java.util.logging.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] One of the most recognized features of Log4j 2 is the performance of the "Asynchronous Loggers".
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j 2 makes use of the LMAX Disruptor.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The library reduces the need for kernel locking and increases the logging performance by a factor of 12.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] For example, in the same environment Log4j 2 can write more than 18,000,000 messages per second, whereas other frameworks like Logback and Log4j 1 just write < 2,000,000 messages per second.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The following table defines the built-in log levels and messages in Log4j, in decreasing order of severity.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The left column lists the log level designation in Log4j and the right column provides a brief description of each log level.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j 2 allows users to define their own log levels.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] A source code generator tool is provided to create Loggers that support custom log levels identically to the built-in log levels.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Custom log levels can either complement or replace the built-in log levels.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j can be configured through a configuration file or through Java code.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Configuration files can be written in XML, JSON, YAML, or properties file format.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Three main components can be defined: Loggers, Appenders, and Layouts.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Configuring logging via a file has the advantage that logging can be turned on or off without modifying the application that uses Log4j.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The application can be allowed to run with logging off until there's a problem, for example, and then logging can be turned back on simply by modifying the configuration file.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The actual outputs are done by **Appenders**.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] There are numerous Appenders available, with descriptive names, such as FileAppender, RollingFileAppender, ConsoleAppender, SocketAppender, SyslogAppender, and SMTPAppender.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j 2 added Appenders that write to Apache Flume, the Java Persistence API, Apache Kafka, NoSQL databases, Memory-mapped files, Random Access files and ZeroMQ endpoints.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Multiple Appenders can be attached to any Logger, so it's possible to log the same information to multiple outputs; for example to a file locally and to a socket listener on another computer.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Appenders use **Layouts** to format log entries.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] A popular way to format one-line-at-a-time log files is PatternLayout, which uses a pattern string, much like the C / C++ function printf.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] There are also HTMLLayout and XMLLayout formatters for use when HTML or XML formats are more convenient, respectively.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Log4j 2 added Layouts for CSV, Graylog Extended Log Format (GELF), JSON, YAML and RFC-5424.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] In Log4j 2, **Filters** can be defined on configuration elements to give more fine-grained control over which log entries should be processed by which Loggers and Appenders.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] In addition to filtering by log level and regular expression matching on the message string, Log4j 2 added burst filters, time filters, filtering by other log event attributes like Markers or Thread Context Map and JSR 223 script filters.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] To find out where a log4j2.xml configuration file was loaded from inspect `getClass().getResource("/log4j2.xml")`.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] There is also an implicit "unconfigured" or "default" configuration of Log4j, that of a Log4j-instrumented Java application which lacks any Log4j configuration.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] This prints to stdout a warning that the program is unconfigured, and the URL to the Log4j web site where details on the warning and configuration may be found.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] As well as printing this warning, an unconfigured Log4j application will only print ERROR or FATAL log entries to standard out.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] TTCC is an acronym for *Time Thread Category Component*.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] A zero-day vulnerability involving remote code execution in Log4j 2, given the descriptor "Log4Shell" (CVE-2021-44228), was found and reported to Apache by Alibaba on November 24, 2021, and published in a tweet on December 9, 2021.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] Affected services include Cloudflare, iCloud, *Minecraft: Java Edition*, Steam, Tencent QQ, and Twitter.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The Apache Software Foundation assigned the maximum CVSS severity rating of 10 to Log4Shell, as millions of servers could be potentially vulnerable to the exploit.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The vulnerability was characterized by cybersecurity firm Tenable as "the single biggest, most critical vulnerability of the last decade" and Lunasec's Free Wortley characterized it as "a design failure of catastrophic proportions".
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] The Canadian Centre for Cyber Security (CCCS) called on organisations to take on immediate action.
[src:log4j-logging-java/log4j] For additional security, from version 2.16.0 onward, all features using JNDI, on which this vulnerability was based, were disabled by default, and support for message lookups removed.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:log4j-logging-java/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Harrington (2000), "the development of the object-oriented paradigm brought about a fundamental change in the way we look at data and the procedures that operate on data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Traditionally, data and procedures have been stored separately: the data and their relationship in a database, the procedures in an application program.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] During the early 1990s, three Dutch mathematicians Guido Bakema, Harm van der Lek, and JanPieter Zwart, continued the development on the work of G.M.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] They focused more on the communication part of the semantics.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In 1997 they formalized the method Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling FCO-IM.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Associations between data objects are described during the database design procedure, such that normalization is an inevitable result of the process.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The simplest style of data warehouse schema.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The star schema consists of a few "fact tables" (possibly only one, justifying the name) referencing any number of "dimension tables".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) [1] is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:log4j-logging-java/structured-data] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
